<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Lemma"
         id="Thm_SpanCompare"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Comparison of span sets</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Read this as: ‘T is defined to be S union v’</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>This means: we are forming a new collection <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math> of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math> by including the vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> in the set of vectors <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Comment</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Thus adding new vectors to a subset <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math> does not necessarily increase the span. Adding a new vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> to <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> only increases the span if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> does not belong to <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>Given a subset <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> and a vector <math>
               <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>, put</para.body>
      </para>
      <math.array column="3">
         <row rowspan="1">
            <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math>
            </cell>
            <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <math>
                  <latex>:=</latex>
               </math>
            </cell>
            <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <math>
                  <latex>S\union \Set{ \Vect{v} }</latex>
               </math>
            </cell>
         </row>
      </math.array>
      <para>
         <para.body>Then <math>
               <latex>\span(S)=\span(T)</latex>
            </math> if and only if <math>
               <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
            </math> is in <math>
               <latex>\span(S)</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider first the case where <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)=\span(T)</latex>
               </math>. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> is a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. But we know that 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math> is in <math>
                        <latex>\span(T)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Why is <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\span(T)</latex>
                        </math>?</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>We know that <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>T</latex>
                           </math>. Therefore</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.array column="3">
                        <row rowspan="1">
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>1\cdot \Vect{v}</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                        </row>
                     </math.array>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>is a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                              <latex>T</latex>
                           </math> and, hence, <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                           </math> is in <math>
                              <latex>\span(T)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>.
			As  <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)=\span(T)</latex>
               </math>, <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
               </math> is also a linear combination of  <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider now that case where <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}= a_1 \Vect{s}_1 + \cdots + a_k \Vect{s}_k</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)</latex>
               </math>. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)=\span(T)</latex>
               </math>. – Now every linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math> is also a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math>. So it remains to show that every linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math> is also a linear combination of vectors in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. – Indeed, if</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{w}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t \Vect{v}\ +\ b_1 \Vect{t}_1 + \cdots + b_r \Vect{t}_r</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>is a linear combination of <math>
                  <latex>T</latex>
               </math>,  then <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{t}_1, \dots ,\Vect{t}_r</latex>
               </math> are in <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>, and we need to show that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{w}</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)</latex>
               </math>. But we know also that</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{w}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t(a_1 \Vect{s}_1+\cdots + a_k \Vect{s}_k)\ +\ b_1 \Vect{t}_1+\cdots + b_r \Vect{t}_r</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>which is a linear combination of vectors from <math>
                  <latex>S</latex>
               </math>. Therefore <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{w}</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\span(S)</latex>
               </math>. This completes the proof.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
